<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900719-0054</DOCNO><DOCID>900719-0054.</DOCID><HL>   `Major' Criminal Actions   Due by U.S. in Sandamp;L Fraud</HL><DATE>07/19/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12</SO><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)</IN><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- A top investigator for the Resolution TrustCorp. said the agency expects &quot;major&quot; criminal actions to bebrought eventually against officials of 40% of the failedsavings-and-loan associations taken over by the government.   James Dudine, assistant director of RTC investigations,said the agency also expects to bring civil actions chargingmalfeasance by directors and officers at 55% of the insolventthrifts. The RTC, created by last year's Sandamp;L legislation tosell off and liquidate hundreds of insolvent thrifts, hastaken over about 450 thrifts and has sold or liquidated about210.</LP><TEXT>   The RTC believes civil claims against accountants will bebrought in 22% of the cases, and against attorneys in about18%, Mr. Dudine said.   RTC investigators also believe about 15% of the failedthrifts colluded with other thrifts in fraudulenttransactions such as joint real-estate deals and loan swaps,he added.   Timothy Ryan, director of the Office of ThriftSupervision, said that agency was concerned that judgesaren't giving sufficiently stiff sentences to those convictedof Sandamp;L fraud. Though the Justice Department has pointed tosome executives who have received as much as 30-yearsentences, that is &quot;the exception,&quot; Mr. Ryan said.</TEXT></DOC>